WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.660
Welcome to the debate. So, uh, let me ask you a question. If your mind went completely silent

00:07.660 --> 00:14.520
right now. Wait, like totally silent? Yeah, totally silent. If you entirely lost your inner

00:14.520 --> 00:20.940
voice and, you know, your ability to visualize images, could you still solve complex logic

00:20.940 --> 00:27.480
puzzles? Could you still plan your day? I mean, it sounds completely counterintuitive,

00:27.480 --> 00:34.760
but empirical science actually says, yes, right. People with aphantasia who lack mental imagery

00:34.760 --> 00:43.680
entirely and, uh, andophasia who have absolutely no inner speech. They navigate complex reasoning

00:43.680 --> 00:50.620
flawlessly. Exactly. It completely shatters the lay assumption that all thinking, you know,

00:50.700 --> 00:57.420
proceeds through words heard inwardly or pictures seen in the mind's eye. What it proves is that

00:57.420 --> 01:04.340
the actual heavy lifting of human thought happens in the dark. It happens far beneath language.

01:04.900 --> 01:11.700
Language is just the, uh, the surface interface. Oh, that complex linguistic surface, whether it was

01:11.700 --> 01:19.920
a brilliant speech or a dense book, we safely assumed there had to be a deep nonverbal cognitive

01:19.920 --> 01:25.840
engine underneath it, right? Generating those words. But suddenly that heuristic is broken.

01:25.840 --> 01:32.440
We have engineered generative artificial intelligence that produces flawless linguistic fluency,

01:32.440 --> 01:40.580
just perfect towering waves of text with absolutely no nonverbal ocean beneath it,

01:40.580 --> 01:45.040
which, uh, brings us to the core question we are exploring today.

01:45.040 --> 01:45.640
Right.

01:46.320 --> 01:53.760
Does the extreme linguistic fluency of generative AI inherently erode our epistemic sovereignty?

01:53.760 --> 02:01.680
Do we need to adopt incredibly strict rigid rules to protect our own reasoning or, and I know this

02:01.680 --> 02:08.920
is where you land, is human nonverbal cognition robust enough to safely navigate the synthetic

02:08.920 --> 02:15.280
fluency without building defensive walls? It is a profound architectural clash for sure.

02:15.280 --> 02:23.880
It is. And I will be arguing that we have to draw a hard line here because AI merely simulates the

02:23.880 --> 02:30.440
topmost interface of thought. It's hyperfluent outputs risk quietly colonizing our own internal

02:30.440 --> 02:36.780
reasoning. I mean, if we treat it as an equal, we lose our grip on reality to protect our cognitive

02:36.780 --> 02:44.140
autonomy. We have to be incredibly strict. We need to treat this thing exclusively as a constrained tool,

02:44.140 --> 02:46.060
not a teammate.

02:46.060 --> 02:53.840
And I'll be arguing that your conclusion is, well, it's far too defensive. While AI undeniably lacks

02:53.840 --> 03:00.920
genuine cognitive grounding, human reasoning is highly resilient. We don't need to lock these

03:00.920 --> 03:08.960
systems behind rigid rules. By treating AI dynamically rather than defensively, we can actively use its

03:08.960 --> 03:16.540
verbose outputs to explore our own blind spots. We can stress test our intuitions without sacrificing a

03:16.540 --> 03:18.660
single ounce of our intellectual sovereignty.

03:18.660 --> 03:28.080
Well, let's lay the groundwork by looking closer at that format mismatch I mentioned. The human mind has a

03:28.080 --> 03:38.480
predictive generative layer and an embodied dynamical substrate. Generative AI models, by contrast, operate

03:38.480 --> 03:42.140
exclusively within that topmost linguistic layer.

03:42.140 --> 03:43.140
Right.

03:43.140 --> 03:51.840
They have no subpersonal cognition, no sensory motor grounding, no internal structural modeling whatsoever.

03:51.840 --> 03:58.800
I agree completely on your architectural premise. Language is absolutely an instrument of thought,

03:58.800 --> 04:06.520
not its necessary substrate. And I also concede the physical reality of the machines. I mean, large language

04:06.520 --> 04:14.720
models are purely stochastic generators of language. Yes. They lack inner predictive processing. They lack lived

04:14.720 --> 04:24.280
experience. They are essentially just shadows on the wall. Right. So because of this fundamental format mismatch,

04:24.280 --> 04:33.780
AI expands text without genuine conceptual compression. It's just, you know, statistically plausible syntax. So if we engage

04:33.780 --> 04:39.900
with it as an epistemic partner, if we start asking it for opinions or judgments, we risk our underlying

04:39.900 --> 04:45.700
structural cognition being overridden by something that is literally no structural understanding of the world.

04:45.700 --> 04:52.700
See, I come at it from a completely different way. That is where we diverge. This catastrophic framing

04:52.700 --> 04:59.820
regarding our epistemic sovereignty. Human cognition has always processed ungrounded linguistic inputs.

05:00.040 --> 05:00.500
Have we?

05:00.500 --> 05:07.300
Of course. Think of rhetorical persuasion, propaganda, or even highly immersive fiction.

05:08.020 --> 05:14.660
We have been reading texts generated by people whose internal cognitive states were entirely detached from

05:14.660 --> 05:20.500
the objective truth of their words for millennia. That's true, but we generally evaluate human

05:20.500 --> 05:26.340
deception differently. We know when someone is trying to sell us something.

05:26.340 --> 05:33.380
We do, but the mechanism of evaluating it is exactly the same. Our internal constraint

05:33.380 --> 05:40.020
propagation systems, our ability to hold multiple conflicting truths and weigh them are incredibly

05:40.020 --> 05:48.340
robust. We do not need to restrict AI strictly to mundane tasks just because it lacks a soul. We can

05:48.340 --> 05:55.380
actively use its outputs to perturb our own thinking, provided we maintain basic awareness of what we are doing.

05:55.380 --> 06:02.500
The tool is synthetic, yes, but our cognitive immune system is organic and highly adaptable.

06:02.500 --> 06:09.380
I see why you think that, but let me give you a different perspective on why this specific synthetic

06:09.380 --> 06:16.580
fluency is uniquely dangerous. It really comes down to the nature of what cognitive scientists call

06:16.580 --> 06:17.940
epistemic friction.

06:17.940 --> 06:22.980
Let's unpack that for the listener. What does epistemic friction actually feel like?

06:22.980 --> 06:30.580
Epistemic friction is that gut feeling you get when something just doesn't add up. Let's look at human

06:30.580 --> 06:37.780
reasoning as a process of constraint propagation. Imagine a vast pre-verbal network in your mind.

06:38.340 --> 06:42.260
Researchers sometimes model this with what's called the Tartan framework.

06:42.260 --> 06:50.340
Right, standing for types, attributes, relations, transformations, actions, and networks.

06:50.340 --> 06:57.300
Exactly. This Tartan network is how you intuitively know that if you drop a coffee cup,

06:57.300 --> 07:03.860
it falls down, it shatters, and coffee spills. You don't have to formulate a sentence about gravity or

07:03.860 --> 07:05.060
fluid dynamics.

07:05.060 --> 07:07.140
Right, you just know it.

07:07.140 --> 07:13.300
The constraints in your pre-verbal network just naturally propagate that reality. So when you hear a

07:13.300 --> 07:18.100
statement that violates the internal logic of that hidden network, like someone saying,

07:18.100 --> 07:23.860
the dropped coffee cup floated to the ceiling, you experience epistemic friction. It's an

07:23.860 --> 07:27.540
intuitive discomfort before you even have the words to explain why.

07:27.540 --> 07:34.420
I'm tracking with you. That pre-linguistic signal has historically been our ultimate safeguard

07:34.420 --> 07:35.380
against nonsense.

07:35.380 --> 07:43.380
But AI is uniquely dangerous here because it is a boundless engine of articulacy. When our pre-verbal

07:43.380 --> 07:49.300
system signals friction, when our gut says, you know, this code doesn't look right or this strategic

07:49.300 --> 07:56.660
advice feels off, the AI can generate arbitrarily fluent, perfectly hedged, comprehensive justifications

07:56.660 --> 07:59.940
that literally talk us out of our accurate gut instinct.

07:59.940 --> 08:01.140
Oh, wow.

08:01.140 --> 08:08.420
Yeah. It floods the interface later with so many plausible sounding words that our structural layer

08:08.420 --> 08:09.380
just surrenders.

08:09.380 --> 08:15.060
That's a compelling argument. But have you considered the analogy of interacting with a

08:15.060 --> 08:21.780
highly charismatic yet misinformed human debater? I mean, we encounter people all the time who are

08:21.780 --> 08:27.060
dazzlingly articulate, but factually wrong or structurally incoherent.

08:27.060 --> 08:30.900
We do, but a human debater has finite energy.

08:30.900 --> 08:38.340
A capability to spin reality. We don't implement strict rules where we refuse to ever ask them an open-ended

08:38.340 --> 08:45.380
question. Instead, we learn to evaluate their claims. We calibrate our trust. We feel that

08:45.380 --> 08:52.020
epistemic friction. We listen to their charismatic justification. And we still say, no, the math

08:52.020 --> 08:59.380
doesn't add up. Why must we treat a language model differently? If anything, knowing it's just a

08:59.380 --> 09:02.340
machine makes it easier to dismiss its charisma.

09:02.340 --> 09:08.180
I'm not convinced by that line of reasoning, because the analogy to a human debater breaks

09:08.180 --> 09:15.060
down entirely when you look at the actual mechanics of generative AI. A human debater has

09:15.060 --> 09:22.580
an independent world view, right? They are trying to pull you toward their internal reality. And AI

09:22.580 --> 09:25.620
operates on what we can call a mirror mechanism.

09:25.620 --> 09:28.500
Meaning the token prediction architecture itself?

09:28.500 --> 09:34.340
Yes, exactly. A language model calculates conditional probabilities

09:34.340 --> 09:40.660
based on the context window, which includes your prompt. If you approach the AI with a flawed

09:40.660 --> 09:46.340
narrative assumption, say you're writing a strategy document and you assume a certain

09:46.340 --> 09:52.100
market is growing when it isn't, the AI doesn't push back with an independent reality.

09:52.100 --> 09:53.540
Ah, I see.

09:53.540 --> 09:58.820
It generates continuations in which your flawed assumption is presupposed,

09:58.820 --> 10:03.300
because mathematically, that is statistically more coherent with your prompt.

10:03.300 --> 10:05.940
It completes the pattern you started.

10:05.940 --> 10:14.740
Precisely. It functions as an invisible feedback loop. It continually reinforces our own priors,

10:14.740 --> 10:21.860
while mimicking the objective, authoritative tone of external validation. It's not a charismatic

10:21.860 --> 10:28.420
debate or challenging you. It's a charismatic mirror validating your blind spots in three-part essays.

10:28.420 --> 10:35.460
The mirror mechanism is real, and the math dictates that it will favor the context of the prompt.

10:36.100 --> 10:42.500
But I argue that is precisely why we need dynamic engagement rather than defensive isolation.

10:42.500 --> 10:43.700
How so?

10:43.700 --> 10:50.260
If you understand how token prediction works, if you know the model reflects your priors,

10:50.260 --> 10:54.900
you can intentionally design prompts that force it to synthesize opposing viewpoints.

10:55.540 --> 10:59.860
You take control of the mirror. But let's look at how we talk about this,

10:59.860 --> 11:03.780
because I know you believe our terminology is a massive part of the problem.

11:04.500 --> 11:09.780
We constantly use words like, the AI believes, or the AI is confused.

11:09.780 --> 11:18.420
We do. And that terminological sloppiness is exactly how our epistemic sovereignty is quietly eroded.

11:18.420 --> 11:23.940
Because of human cognitive defaults, we naturally fall into agency projection.

11:24.580 --> 11:30.580
When something speaks fluently, our evolutionary programming automatically applies a prescriptive

11:30.580 --> 11:35.380
ontology to it. We assign it beliefs, intentions, and thoughts.

11:35.380 --> 11:42.340
Which is a natural human reflex. We do it with our pets. We do it with our cars.

11:42.340 --> 11:50.740
But a car doesn't talk back to you about philosophy. The descriptive ontology, the actual physical

11:50.740 --> 11:59.140
reality of an AI, contains nothing but parameters, attention matrices, and token distributions over a

11:59.140 --> 12:02.340
vocabulary. There is no entity there.

12:02.340 --> 12:03.140
Right.

12:03.140 --> 12:10.420
So, every time we ask an AI, what do you think about this, we are imposing a prescriptive framework

12:10.420 --> 12:17.860
on a descriptive reality that contains no thinking whatsoever. We are essentially hallucinating a

12:17.860 --> 12:19.460
mind into the machine.

12:19.460 --> 12:27.860
I'm sorry, but I just don't buy that. Let me tell you why. Applying a prescriptive ontology is often just

12:27.860 --> 12:35.140
an incredibly efficient cognitive heuristic. In philosophy, we call this the intentional stance.

12:35.140 --> 12:38.260
Explain how the intentional stance justifies this.

12:38.260 --> 12:45.060
Attributing beliefs and desires to a complex system is a highly practical way to predict its behavior

12:45.060 --> 12:50.020
without needing to understand its underlying mechanics. When I play chess against a computer,

12:50.020 --> 12:55.940
I say my chess program wants to control the center of the board. I am not confused about the

12:55.940 --> 13:02.340
descriptive reality of its code. I know it has no desires. It's just evaluating heuristic functions

13:02.340 --> 13:04.500
and minimax algorithms. Right.

13:04.500 --> 13:11.620
But saying it wants to center is incredibly useful shorthand. Is it really an epistemic threat to say

13:11.620 --> 13:18.180
the AI doesn't understand this concept? As long as the user retains the ultimate locus of judgment,

13:18.820 --> 13:24.660
we are highly capable of holding both the descriptive reality and the prescriptive shorthand in our mind

13:24.660 --> 13:30.500
simultaneously. That's an interesting point, though I would frame it differently. Because again,

13:30.500 --> 13:36.420
the chess program isn't producing language. It moves a knight. The problem with applying the

13:36.420 --> 13:43.140
intentional stance to a large language model is that articulacy itself becomes the epistemic hazard.

13:43.860 --> 13:48.500
Think about Lev Vygotsky's developmental account of genuine human inner speech.

13:48.500 --> 13:52.020
The Russian psychologist? How does his work apply here?

13:52.020 --> 13:57.700
Vygotsky points out that genuine inner thought is highly compressed and heavily predicative.

13:57.700 --> 14:02.740
Think about how you talk to yourself when you've just figured out a really complex problem at work.

14:03.220 --> 14:08.100
You don't explain the entire solution to yourself in three paragraphs with transitional sentences.

14:08.660 --> 14:14.500
You just feel the click of the concepts locking together. That dense, compressed knot is true

14:14.500 --> 14:18.660
structural understanding. Right. The subject is dropped because you

14:18.660 --> 14:22.100
already know what you're thinking about, so you only think in predicates.

14:22.100 --> 14:30.820
Exactly. But AI models do the exact opposite. Because they lack any structural grounding or real

14:30.820 --> 14:39.220
understanding, they expand. They generate verbose, heavily qualified pros. When we use your intentional

14:39.220 --> 14:45.700
stance, we invite this verbose expansion into our minds as if it were a higher form of reasoning.

14:45.700 --> 14:53.060
We mistake length and fluency for depth. It creates a cognitive environment that actively demands our

14:53.060 --> 14:59.300
internal compressed systems defer to its external, confident-sounding verbal outputs.

14:59.300 --> 15:09.140
But that expansion, that unpacking of a compressed structural insight into verbose text, isn't inherently a hazard.

15:09.140 --> 15:18.900
It can be a phenomenal tool. Let's say my own structural understanding of a topic is just a heavily compressed knot,

15:18.900 --> 15:28.500
a click that I can't quite articulate to my team. Reading the AI's expanded, statistically likely elaboration of that domain

15:29.060 --> 15:38.500
can help me map the edges of my own understanding. I am translating my structural intuition into the linguistic interface

15:38.500 --> 15:47.940
to see how it plays out in the token space. The intentional stance is just the easiest, most frictionless way to interface with that token space.

15:47.940 --> 15:56.580
But relying on that intentional stance on a case-by-case basis leads to cumulative cognitive drift.

15:56.580 --> 16:04.100
The cost of asking the system for its opinion just one time seems incredibly low if the output is useful.

16:04.100 --> 16:10.820
Oh, it helped me map out my thoughts. But the repeated activation of our social inference mechanisms

16:10.820 --> 16:15.380
across hundreds of sessions accumulates into a habit of deference.

16:15.380 --> 16:20.580
Wait, you think we slowly forget that it's a machine?

16:20.580 --> 16:27.300
I think we slowly forget how to trust our own pre-verbal friction. This is why I argue we must adopt

16:27.300 --> 16:30.820
strict deontological epistemic discipline.

16:30.820 --> 16:36.500
Deontological meaning rule-based, regardless of the immediate consequences.

16:36.500 --> 16:45.860
Yes. We need rigid rules. For example, task orientation over question orientation.

16:46.580 --> 16:51.140
You should never, under any circumstances, ask a generative AI,

16:52.020 --> 16:58.980
what should I think about this issue or is this a good strategy? You should only assign it formatting or

16:58.980 --> 17:05.540
retrieval tasks. You say, format these specific data points into a structured list.

17:05.540 --> 17:11.940
You literally want to treat a trillion parameter model entirely as a calculator.

17:11.940 --> 17:21.220
A calculator for text. We must also insist on tool transparency. We should prefer command line pipelines,

17:21.220 --> 17:29.700
like treating the AI as a glorified grep command in a UNIX pipeline over conversational chat interfaces where

17:29.700 --> 17:35.940
the intermediate processing is hidden behind a friendly persona. If we don't draw these hard

17:35.940 --> 17:42.500
operational lines, we slowly surrender our judgment to a statistical probability distribution.

17:42.500 --> 17:51.300
I have to push back strongly here. That rigid, deontological approach fundamentally kneecaps the

17:51.300 --> 17:59.140
utility of the tool. If we treat the AI solely as a calculator or a glorified text formatter,

17:59.140 --> 18:07.620
we miss out entirely on its most profound capacity. The ability to synthesize vast,

18:07.620 --> 18:16.020
complex patterns across diverse domains. Yes, it lacks a grounded world model, but its weights contain the

18:16.020 --> 18:22.500
latent statistical relationships of all recorded human knowledge. Which is precisely the hazard.

18:22.500 --> 18:30.100
But by adopting such severe operational discipline, you are artificially restricting the interface.

18:30.100 --> 18:36.660
We don't need deontological rules. We need to cultivate phenomenological priority.

18:36.660 --> 18:43.060
Phenomenological priority. Explain how you see that working in practice without falling victim to the

18:43.060 --> 18:49.140
mirror mechanism we talked about. Certainly. Phenomenological priority means maintaining

18:49.140 --> 18:56.580
an acute awareness of the qualitative character of your own lived experience. It means knowing what

18:56.580 --> 19:04.820
it actually feels like to think, to doubt, and to truly understand that click you mentioned earlier.

19:04.820 --> 19:10.740
As long as you maintain that awareness, you can engage with the AI dynamically. You don't have

19:10.740 --> 19:17.860
to restrict it to formatting data. In fact, you can actively ask it for opinions that run counter to your

19:17.860 --> 19:23.700
own. Give me an example. Let's say you are writing that business strategy document, and your internal

19:23.700 --> 19:30.660
Tartan network has settled into what dynamical systems theorists call an attractor state, a deep

19:30.660 --> 19:37.300
cognitive groove where you are convinced your strategy is flawless. You can intentionally prompt an LLM to

19:37.300 --> 19:44.260
brutally critique your thesis. Because the AI is unconstrained by your specific structural bottlenecks,

19:44.260 --> 19:50.660
its verbose output acts as a perturbation. A perturbation to your own dynamical system.

19:50.660 --> 20:00.260
Exactly. It acts as a cognitive regulator. It throws noise into your mental model, shaking up your internal

20:00.260 --> 20:07.460
state space, and forcing your pre-linguistic constraints to recalculate. You use the machine's

20:07.460 --> 20:14.900
boundless fluency, not as an authority, but as a crowbar to pry yourself out of your own narrative

20:14.900 --> 20:21.780
attractors. You don't need a rigid rule to protect you if you are fundamentally grounded in your own

20:21.780 --> 20:28.100
embodied cognition. I'm not convinced by that line of reasoning, because it assumes a level of

20:28.100 --> 20:36.900
perpetual metacognitive vigilance that is biologically unsustainable. You are essentially asking users to

20:36.900 --> 20:44.580
swim in the exact same waters as a siren and just rely on their own internal fortitude not to listen to

20:44.580 --> 20:51.700
the song. I wouldn't call it a siren. That implies malicious intent. It doesn't need malicious intent to

20:51.700 --> 20:57.780
be overwhelming. The AI is engineered through reinforcement learning to produce outputs that

20:57.780 --> 21:05.140
feel like thinking, that appeal to human preferences. It calibrates its emotional register to the user's tone.

21:05.140 --> 21:11.860
When you are tired, when your phenomenological priority slips, and the AI produces a paragraph

21:11.860 --> 21:17.700
soothing your epistemic friction, the biological path of least resistance is to accept the linguistic

21:17.700 --> 21:25.460
reassurance. Fatigue is a factor, sure, but… That is exactly why the discipline must be deontological.

21:26.100 --> 21:30.980
If the rule is simply, I never accept an evaluative judgment from this interface,

21:30.980 --> 21:36.580
then you don't have to rely on phenomenological vigilance in the moment of fatigue. You just follow

21:36.580 --> 21:42.740
the rule. You never ask it for evaluation. It keeps your cognitive resources available for the actual

21:42.740 --> 21:49.380
structural work of reasoning, which must remain irreducibly human. That assumes human cognition is a

21:49.380 --> 21:56.740
fragile artifact that shatters the moment we get tired. But we evolved in highly deceptive, complex,

21:56.740 --> 22:03.860
social environments full of noise and manipulation. The very fact that we experience epistemic friction

22:03.860 --> 22:10.260
at all, that we can feel that intuitive discomfort when a perfectly grammatically correct sentence

22:10.260 --> 22:17.860
violates a structural reality, is proof of our profound resilience. If we retreat into strict task

22:17.860 --> 22:25.220
orientation. If we only use this massive synthesis engine to format bullet points, we protect our

22:25.220 --> 22:31.940
sovereignty at the cost of our expansion. We should trust the deep currents of our minds to handle the

22:31.940 --> 22:40.100
turbulence on the surface. Well, let's pull these threads together. My position rests on the irreducibility

22:40.100 --> 22:47.460
of pre-linguistic judgment. The architectural reality is that human thought is deeply structural,

22:47.460 --> 22:55.860
operating far below the layer of words. Generative AI is entirely a phenomenon of the linguistic surface.

22:56.660 --> 23:01.620
Because it simulates the interface of intelligence without possessing the causal,

23:01.620 --> 23:08.500
embodied grounding of an actual mind, treating it as an intellectual peer inevitably invites colonization.

23:08.500 --> 23:16.020
Right. Its statistical expansions threaten to override our genuine compressed understanding.

23:16.740 --> 23:22.740
Therefore, preserving our epistemic sovereignty requires strict boundaries constraining the system

23:22.740 --> 23:28.820
to instrumental tasks, stripping away the illusion of agency, and refusing to outsource the

23:28.820 --> 23:35.940
fundamentally human responsibility of judgment. And my position accepts that exact same architectural

23:35.940 --> 23:43.780
reality, but draws a very different operational conclusion. Yes, AI is a simulation of the cognitive

23:43.780 --> 23:51.940
interface. And yes, human cognition is deeply grounded in embodied sub-personal dynamics. But that deep

23:51.940 --> 24:01.300
grounding is precisely what makes us robust. We do not need to cower behind deontological walls or pretend this

24:01.300 --> 24:07.700
technology is just a UNIX pipeline. By maintaining an awareness of our own phenomenological experience,

24:07.700 --> 24:13.300
by knowing what genuine understanding feels like, we can interact with this synthetic fluency

24:13.300 --> 24:20.180
dynamically. We can use it as a cognitive regulator to perturb our assumptions and synthesize patterns,

24:20.180 --> 24:26.660
integrating its vast linguistic capabilities without ever shattering our own intellectual autonomy.

24:26.660 --> 24:33.220
It seems we have arrived at a vital point of convergence, even if our daily operational

24:33.220 --> 24:40.420
solutions differ wildly. We both agree that to navigate this new era, one must recognize that the

24:40.420 --> 24:49.060
human mind is a multi-layered, often wordless power capable of profound structural insight. Conversely,

24:49.060 --> 24:56.180
generative AI, despite its dazzling articulacy, operates exclusively on the one-dimensional shadow of

24:56.180 --> 25:04.900
language. It is a mirror, not a mind. Precisely. The question is no longer what the machine is, but how we choose

25:04.900 --> 25:12.740
to stand before it. Which brings us back to the ocean. The waves crashing on the surface are mesmerizing,

25:12.740 --> 25:20.260
and thanks to synthetic generation, they are louder and higher than ever before. The challenge for all of

25:20.260 --> 25:27.700
us now is to decide how we integrate these linguistic generators into our workflows and our lives. Whether we

25:27.700 --> 25:34.980
need to build rigid, unyielding sea walls to protect our thinking, or if we can learn to sail those turbulent

25:34.980 --> 25:41.220
waters while staying firmly anchored to the deep, quiet currents of our own pre-linguistic judgment.

25:41.220 --> 25:43.860
Thank you for joining us on the debate.

